      "content": "Apologies for the goblin misstep. Let's dive straight into the science of the Maillard reaction and the role of moisture content in your dough. The Maillard reaction, a complex chemical process, occurs between amino acids and reducing sugars when exposed to heat, typically above 140°C (284°F). This reaction is responsible for the browning and flavor development in your bread's crust.\n\nMoisture content in the dough plays a significant role in this reaction. A higher moisture content can indeed slow down the Maillard reaction. This is because the water in the dough competes with the amino acids and sugars, making it harder for them to react with each other. Think of it as a crowded party where the more people there are, the harder it is for any two people to find each other and dance together. In the case of your bread, the water molecules in the dough are like the partygoers, making it more challenging for the amino acids and sugars to come together and perform the Maillard reaction.\n\nTo achieve a good crust, you'll want to aim for a moisture content that allows the Maillard reaction to occur efficiently. This typically means a dough with a moisture content of around 60-70%. However, the exact moisture content",
