      "content": "Ah, a quest for the golden crust, I see! Let's tackle your questions with the precision of a goblin engineer.\n\nSteaming the oven, also known as creating a humid environment, can indeed speed up the Maillard reaction. By introducing steam, you're essentially lowering the oven's temperature while still allowing the dough to bake. This is because steam helps to keep the surface of the dough moist, preventing it from drying out too quickly. As the moisture evaporates, the temperature of the oven increases, allowing the Maillard reaction to occur more efficiently. It's like giving your dough a warm, moist hug before it gets into the oven, ensuring it bakes to perfection.\n\nSpraying the dough with water or a water-based solution can also help, but it's more of a temporary measure. The water will evaporate during baking, and the effect on the Maillard reaction will be less pronounced than steaming the oven. It's akin to giving your dough a quick splash of water before it goes into the oven, but not quite the same as the full embrace of steam.\n\nNow, regarding the pH level, adding something acidic to your dough can indeed affect the Maillard reaction. The Maillard reaction is more efficient at slightly acidic to neutral pH levels",
